  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT253-kilavi">piriviṭait tōḻi vaṟpuṟuttatu(C1: varavuṟuttatu).</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">The confidante encouraging in the time of separation. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT253">
          <l> kēḷā rākuvar tōḻi kēṭpiṉ</l>
          <l> viḻumitu kaḻiva tāyiṉu nekiḻnūṟ</l>
          <l> pūccē raṇaiyiṟ peruṅkaviṉ ṟolaintaniṉ</l>
          <l> ṉāṭṭuyar kēṭpi ṉīṭalar mātō</l>
          <l> volikaḻai nivanta vōṅkumalai cāraṟ</l>
          <l> pulipukā vuṟutta pulavunāṟu kallaḷai</l>
          <l> yāṟuceṉ mākkaḷ cēkkuṅ</l>
          <l> kōṭuyar piṟaṅkaṉ malaiyiṟan tōrē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>He will not have heard [it], <note place="foot">Srin. proposes to read <term xml:base="ta">ākuvar</term> here as a presumptive future: "he will not hear it/have
            heard it" (thus also T.V.G.).</note> friend. If he hears [it],</l>
          <l rend="indent2">even if something excellent passes by,</l>
          <l>will he really delay further, if he hears of your daily misery,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">great beauty lost on the common <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">cēr aṇaiyiṉ</term> might be the bed where the lovers used to join,
            and then the <term xml:lang="ta">nekiḻ nūl pū </term> could be read as a metonymic
            apposition for her. Otherwise <term xml:lang="ta">cēr</term> can simply be read a the
            link between <term xml:lang="ta">pū</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">aṇai</term> , a bed
            joined with flowers, although one would think a flower decoration on the bed would
            presuppose HIS presence.</note> bed, a flower on a thread,</l>
          <l rend="indent8">wasting away <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">nekiḻ nūl pū</term> : meaning and relation of that phrase are not
            clear. It can be taken as a metaphor for her solitary wasting away (cf. KT 9). It can
            also be connected with <term xml:lang="ta">cēr</term> (thus T.V.G.): a bed "where
            flowers are joined on a thread, [now] wilting". This might refer to a/the flower garland
            with which SHE has adorned the bed expecting HIS return, and which now fades, just like
            herself.</note>
          </l>
          <l>– he who traversed the mountains, glistening high on the peaks,</l>
          <l rend="indent">where people going [their] way rest</l>
          <l rend="indent2">in stony holes smelling of the flesh the tiger has stored for food</l>
          <l rend="indent4">on the high mountain slope</l>
          <l rend="indent6">where sounding bamboo has grown high?</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
